1 WHEREAS, Bob Baumann was a champion of Louisiana industry at every level of
2 the legislative process and a persistent voice of reason on questions of pipelines, refining,
3 petrochemicals, and the broader industrial activity that drives the state's economy, drawing
4 on a depth of technical and historical knowledge that made him a trusted resource for
5 legislators, agency officials, and industry advocates alike, on whichever side of an issue they
6 happened to find themselves; and
7 WHEREAS, following his retirement from the university, Bob Baumann opened the
8 next chapter of his career as a principal of Hood Baumann and Associates, where he
9 counseled and represented some of the most significant energy enterprises operating in
10 Louisiana, including Shell Oil, ConocoPhillips, Enbridge, TC Energy, and Phillips 66, and
11 continued to bring his characteristic care and seriousness to the work of Louisiana energy
12 policy until the final days of his life; and
13 WHEREAS, beyond his roles in research and advocacy, Baumann remained a
14 stalwart supporter of his academic home in the LSU Department of Geography and
15 Anthropology, securing critical funding for the renovation of the Departmental Alumni
16 Seminar Room and, with his family, establishing the Robert H. Baumann Family
17 Scholarship Fund to support outstanding students in the sciences for years to come; and
18 WHEREAS, all who worked with Bob Baumann over the course of his long career
19 appreciated his graciousness, his integrity, and his unmistakable northeast accent softened
20 by decades of Louisiana hospitality, and knew him as a generous mentor, a candid counselor,
21 and a true gentleman of the capitol; and
22 WHEREAS, from the front porch of his office on Spanish Town Road, affectionately
23 known to those who passed through it as the "Policy Porch," Bob Baumann hosted
24 legislators, lobbyists, agency officials, students, reporters, and friends for wide-ranging
25 conversation on anything and everything happening at the capitol, holding open a kind of
26 standing seminar on Louisiana public life that no other forum could replicate; and
27 WHEREAS, Bob Baumann was a mentor in the fullest sense of the word, generous
28 with his time, his sage advice, and his wealth of knowledge, and a great many of those who
29 today carry forward Louisiana's energy and industrial policy work owe some part of their
30 professional formation to an afternoon, an introduction, or a candid piece of counsel from
